00:01:35,234 --> 00:01:37,434
I mean this in terms of
design of the people

28
00:01:37,434 --> 00:01:39,167
putting this into Google Earth

29
00:01:39,167 --> 00:01:40,767
rather than the actual design
of Google Earth

30
00:01:40,767 --> 00:01:43,100
or any of the other
virtual globes

31
00:01:43,100 --> 00:01:45,701
or Google map-type tools.

32
00:01:45,701 --> 00:01:47,767
And to do this,
I'm gonna explore lessons

33
00:01:47,767 --> 00:01:49,067
from other technologies,

34
00:01:49,067 --> 00:01:50,767
so I'm gonna talk about
some other technologies

35
00:01:50,767 --> 00:01:52,567
and how they developed.

36
00:01:52,567 --> 00:01:54,400
Uh, I'm gonna de--
deconstruct

37
00:01:54,400 --> 00:01:55,734
a couple of projects

38
00:01:55,734 --> 00:01:59,133
from a design
point of view, so...

39
00:01:59,133 --> 00:02:02,334
Okay, so here I go,
off on my tangent.

40
00:02:02,334 --> 00:02:04,601
Uh, polygons rock.
They're really good.

41
00:02:04,601 --> 00:02:07,734
Um...what happens is if--

42
00:02:07,734 --> 00:02:09,834
if you look at Google Earth,
you'll see there's lots

43
00:02:09,834 --> 00:02:11,601
of content which has--

44
00:02:11,601 --> 00:02:13,367
which is in the form
of place marks.

45
00:02:13,367 --> 00:02:14,767
The place marks
are a very common way

46
00:02:14,767 --> 00:02:17,767
of putting information
in Google Earth and...

47
00:02:17,767 --> 00:02:21,834
Oop.

48
00:02:21,834 --> 00:02:23,634
There's one there.

49
00:02:23,634 --> 00:02:26,501
That's the, uh, Albert Memorial
in Hyde Park in London.

50
00:02:26,501 --> 00:02:31,200
And I mention this one because
I did a--

51
00:02:31,200 --> 00:02:33,100
a teaching exercise in London

52
00:02:33,100 --> 00:02:34,534
at the royal
geographical society,

53
00:02:34,534 --> 00:02:36,167
which is very close to this.

54
00:02:36,167 --> 00:02:39,067
And I had to teach them
about how to use GPS.

55
00:02:39,067 --> 00:02:40,634
And I gave them GPSs
and I said,

56
00:02:40,634 --> 00:02:43,334
"go out and mark
the Albert Memorial,"

57
00:02:43,334 --> 00:02:45,100
and the picture of it
is down there.

58
00:02:45,100 --> 00:02:46,701
And what I didn't say,

59
00:02:46,701 --> 00:02:48,167
and I deliberately
didn't tell them

60
00:02:48,167 --> 00:02:49,400
is how they were
supposed to mark it.

61
00:02:49,400 --> 00:02:51,033
So I showed them
how to mark points.

62
00:02:51,033 --> 00:02:53,133
And I said,
"just go out and mark it

63
00:02:53,133 --> 00:02:55,701
the best way you think."

64
00:02:55,701 --> 00:02:57,467
and what they did
is they actually went out

65
00:02:57,467 --> 00:02:59,234
and marked a polygon.

66
00:02:59,234 --> 00:03:01,467
So they actually went out
and they marked that square

67
00:03:01,467 --> 00:03:03,834
rather than marking it
as a point.

68
00:03:03,834 --> 00:03:05,634
Which tells you that it--

69
00:03:05,634 --> 00:03:07,434
these are social scientists
I was talking to.

70
00:03:07,434 --> 00:03:10,234
They aren't big on GIS
or anything.

71
00:03:10,234 --> 00:03:13,334
And they just get the idea
that, actually,

72
00:03:13,334 --> 00:03:15,567
the picture you can see,
the Albert Memorial,

73
00:03:15,567 --> 00:03:17,334
isn't a point.

74
00:03:17,334 --> 00:03:20,467
It's more than a point.
It's actually an area.

75
00:03:20,467 --> 00:03:22,767
And the way it works
in GIS

76
00:03:22,767 --> 00:03:26,033
is lots of data is held
in polygons

77
00:03:26,033 --> 00:03:27,767
as tables of data.

78
00:03:27,767 --> 00:03:29,434
So there's
multiple bits of data

79
00:03:29,434 --> 00:03:32,334
held within polygons.

80
00:03:32,334 --> 00:03:37,033
Um, I thought I'd better
show you a better example.

81
00:03:37,033 --> 00:03:40,400
So in GIS, as I said,
polygons are a lot more common.

82
00:03:40,400 --> 00:03:44,200
Uh, this is an image
of Big Island Hawaii.

83
00:03:44,200 --> 00:03:46,267
And its lava flows
you can see in color

84
00:03:46,267 --> 00:03:49,234
coming down the Mauna Loa
volcano there.

85
00:03:49,234 --> 00:03:51,634
And each of those has to be
a polygon.

86
00:03:51,634 --> 00:03:56,033
You can't mark those different
historical flows of lava

87
00:03:56,033 --> 00:03:57,200
as a point.

88
00:03:57,200 --> 00:03:58,467
And there's lots of analysis

89
00:03:58,467 --> 00:04:01,133
for things like
volcanic hazard go on

90
00:04:01,133 --> 00:04:02,300
with that sort of data.

91
00:04:02,300 --> 00:04:04,834
So it's held in
a GIS system.

92
00:04:04,834 --> 00:04:06,467
And what goes with polygons

93
00:04:06,467 --> 00:04:08,334
is what's called
an attribute table.

94
00:04:08,334 --> 00:04:10,834
So there's lots--there's a whole
table full of data.

95
00:04:10,834 --> 00:04:13,467
I actually just pulled an image
of any old attribute table,

96
00:04:13,467 --> 00:04:16,234
so they don't actually
match up here.

97
00:04:16,234 --> 00:04:18,834
But, uh, you can see
that you have rows,

98
00:04:18,834 --> 00:04:22,100
which is--each polygon
has a set of data

99
00:04:22,100 --> 00:04:24,400
and you have
the attributes there.

100
00:04:24,400 --> 00:04:27,000
So what I've highlighted there
is slope.

101
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:29,767
So each of those lava flows
you can imagine having a slope.

102
00:04:29,767 --> 00:04:32,634
And that helps in the modeling
of where lava will go

103
00:04:32,634 --> 00:04:34,567
in the future.

104
00:04:34,567 --> 00:04:37,000
And there's an esri Google
tie-up now,

105
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:38,567
and what I'm pondering,

106
00:04:38,567 --> 00:04:40,701
and I'd be interested
to know the answer to,

107
00:04:40,701 --> 00:04:45,767
is how all the data
that's held as polygons

108
00:04:45,767 --> 00:04:48,767
in attribute table is gonna get
transferred into Google

109
00:04:48,767 --> 00:04:51,367
if we don't start
using polygons more.

110
00:04:51,367 --> 00:04:55,367
And when I talk to GIS people
about Google Earth,

111
00:04:55,367 --> 00:04:56,767
the thing they often
come up with

112
00:04:56,767 --> 00:04:58,734
is they start talking
about polygons

113
00:04:58,734 --> 00:05:01,834
and how it's the central way
that they control data.

114
00:05:01,834 --> 00:05:04,834
Okay, so briefly,
what can you do with this?

115
00:05:04,834 --> 00:05:07,300
Well, uh, I've had a go
at building a tool

116
00:05:07,300 --> 00:05:08,634
that works with Google Earth,

117
00:05:08,634 --> 00:05:10,834
and this is just
some sample data.

118
00:05:10,834 --> 00:05:12,634
I've produced
some random polygons.

119
00:05:12,634 --> 00:05:14,834
They could be administered
regions, whatever.

120
00:05:14,834 --> 00:05:17,701
And this is in
the Darfur region.

121
00:05:17,701 --> 00:05:21,234
And the yellow and orange marks
you can see there,

122
00:05:21,234 --> 00:05:24,534
those are, um, damaged villages
in Darfur,

123
00:05:24,534 --> 00:05:27,367
and the red flames
are destroyed images.

124
00:05:27,367 --> 00:05:29,767
And I just counted them up
and attached in a table

125
00:05:29,767 --> 00:05:31,534
to those polygons.

126
00:05:31,534 --> 00:05:36,634
And it allows you to produce
thematic map--

127
00:05:36,634 --> 00:05:38,367
thematic maps.

128
00:05:38,367 --> 00:05:41,767
Um, and you can then,
with the tool that we produced,

129
00:05:41,767 --> 00:05:43,767
you can automatically color them
in different ways

130
00:05:43,767 --> 00:05:45,734
on the fly in Google Earth.

131
00:05:45,734 --> 00:05:47,734
So in all kinds of teaching
situations,

132
00:05:47,734 --> 00:05:49,701
that's a--a useful thing.

133
00:05:49,701 --> 00:05:51,133
I'm not gonna go into
the technical details

134
00:05:51,133 --> 00:05:52,567
of how you did that.

135
00:05:52,567 --> 00:05:54,567
If someone wants to ask me
afterwards, I'll tell them.

136
00:05:54,567 --> 00:05:56,734
Um, but the nice thing is,

137
00:05:56,734 --> 00:05:59,067
I just got some
successful funding through

138
00:05:59,067 --> 00:06:00,300
to play around with this,

139
00:06:00,300 --> 00:06:01,968
and the tool I produced

140
00:06:01,968 --> 00:06:03,868
wasn't in a form
that I could release.

141
00:06:03,868 --> 00:06:06,734
And what we're gonna go on
is produce a customization

142
00:06:06,734 --> 00:06:09,367
of Google Maps and play around
with this idea some more.

143
00:06:09,367 --> 00:06:12,334
So you'll see some more things
about this in the future.

144
00:06:12,334 --> 00:06:15,033
Okay, so on to the talk
proper, really.

145
00:06:15,033 --> 00:06:19,234
And to talk about, um,

146
00:06:19,234 --> 00:06:21,167
usability,
GeoWeb usability.

147
00:06:21,167 --> 00:06:23,300
How to design things well
to go into

148
00:06:23,300 --> 00:06:26,934
GeoWeb applications.

149
00:06:26,934 --> 00:06:28,601
And off, really,
on another tangent here.

150
00:06:28,601 --> 00:06:30,834
This is from a drugs education
project

151
00:06:30,834 --> 00:06:32,367
in the U.K. I heard about.

152
00:06:32,367 --> 00:06:35,734
And they gave out pencils as
part of their drugs education

153
00:06:35,734 --> 00:06:38,734
with that message on, saying,
"It's cool not to do drugs."

154
00:06:38,734 --> 00:06:40,968
Now, the thing about pencils
is you sharpen them,

155
00:06:40,968 --> 00:06:43,000
and letters disappear.

156
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:46,567
In which case, the message
of course changes a little.

157
00:06:46,567 --> 00:06:48,300
And then you sharpen it
a bit more,

158
00:06:48,300 --> 00:06:51,067
and it gets even more emphatic
about what you should do.

159
00:06:51,067 --> 00:06:53,400
So they printed up
loads of these pencils

160
00:06:53,400 --> 00:06:54,734
and sent them out.

161
00:06:54,734 --> 00:06:58,667
And then, of course, they had
to not use them again.

162
00:06:58,667 --> 00:07:01,200
Which goes to prove
a great saying of mine

163
00:07:01,200 --> 00:07:02,701
in most of what I do,
which is,

164
00:07:02,701 --> 00:07:05,901
"Just because we can
does not mean we should."

165
00:07:05,901 --> 00:07:08,033
Which is a very cheeky
thing to do, to say,

166
00:07:08,033 --> 00:07:09,868
actually standing
in a Google office

167
00:07:09,868 --> 00:07:12,033
built on things
which are very good

168
00:07:12,033 --> 00:07:13,367
for very good reasons.

169
00:07:13,367 --> 00:07:17,567
Um...so that's
a kind of back story.

170
00:07:17,567 --> 00:07:19,767
The 21st century challenge,
I think,

171
00:07:19,767 --> 00:07:22,868
uh, the central challenge
of our time

172
00:07:22,868 --> 00:07:24,801
is going to be
global warming.

173
00:07:24,801 --> 00:07:29,901
And as a scientist who works
with scientists as well,

174
00:07:29,901 --> 00:07:32,267
it's communicating science
change to the public.

175
00:07:32,267 --> 00:07:34,100
We have to have them
understand what's going on

176
00:07:34,100 --> 00:07:35,567
to make decisions.

177
00:07:35,567 --> 00:07:37,767
Because if we don't persuade
them to stop using planes,

178
00:07:37,767 --> 00:07:39,901
we're not going to solve
global warming.

179
00:07:39,901 --> 00:07:42,067
So it's the central challenge.

180
00:07:42,067 --> 00:07:44,400
And I think the GeoWeb
is the key tool

181
00:07:44,400 --> 00:07:47,100
in that battle
of trying to explain

182
00:07:47,100 --> 00:07:51,167
global warming science
to the public.

183
00:07:51,167 --> 00:07:52,634
And David Attenborough.

184
00:07:52,634 --> 00:07:54,067
I saw him at a Google Earth--

185
00:07:54,067 --> 00:07:56,367
uh, Google outreach launch
in London.

186
00:07:56,367 --> 00:07:58,534
Put this a lot better
than I ever could.

187
00:07:58,534 --> 00:08:00,300
And he said Google Earth is

188
00:08:00,300 --> 00:08:02,901
"a weapon of unparalleled value
in the hands of all of us

189
00:08:02,901 --> 00:08:07,100
who care about this greatly
imperiled world."

190
00:08:07,100 --> 00:08:09,868
so, uh, that's the importance.
That's what we're going for.

191
00:08:09,868 --> 00:08:13,834
That's why considering these
is particularly important,

192
00:08:13,834 --> 00:08:16,567
I think,
in solving these problems.

193
00:08:16,567 --> 00:08:19,734
Okay, so I said I'd talk
about other technologies

194
00:08:19,734 --> 00:08:22,667
and what lessons we could learn
from other technologies.

195
00:08:22,667 --> 00:08:25,200
This gartner's hype cycle,

196
00:08:25,200 --> 00:08:27,267
and it applies to some
technologies, as I said.

197
00:08:27,267 --> 00:08:28,934
Not all of them,
but lots of them go through

198
00:08:28,934 --> 00:08:30,267
this sort of thing.

199
00:08:30,267 --> 00:08:32,234
And what you've got
on the left axis

200
00:08:32,234 --> 00:08:33,334
is visibility.

201
00:08:33,334 --> 00:08:36,501
So the visibility
of the technology

202
00:08:36,501 --> 00:08:39,133
and time on the bottom axis.

203
00:08:39,133 --> 00:08:42,000
And obviously, start with,
there's no technology invented.

204
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:43,667
And then it's invented.

205
00:08:43,667 --> 00:08:46,434
So you have the technology
trigger.

206
00:08:46,434 --> 00:08:50,501
And then everyone gets
very overexcited about it.

207
00:08:50,501 --> 00:08:53,167
And then they realize that they
got overexcited about it,

208
00:08:53,167 --> 00:08:55,834
and actually it doesn't work
in ways people thought it would.

209
00:08:55,834 --> 00:09:00,000
And then finally, people work
out how to use things well.

210
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:02,767
And we end up with a platter
of productivity.

211
00:09:02,767 --> 00:09:06,167
Now, I like this, but I think
it's a bit overcomplicated.

212
00:09:06,167 --> 00:09:07,901
So to explain it in a short
period of time,

213
00:09:07,901 --> 00:09:09,234
I've kind of simplified it.

214
00:09:09,234 --> 00:09:12,234
And I just go with,
there's the old.

215
00:09:12,234 --> 00:09:15,400
There's the wrong.

216
00:09:15,400 --> 00:09:17,601
And there's the right.

217
00:09:17,601 --> 00:09:21,467
So let's have a look
at some technologies.

218
00:09:21,467 --> 00:09:24,567
Watches, and I'm gonna have some
audience participation here.

219
00:09:24,567 --> 00:09:26,534
So old.

220
00:09:26,534 --> 00:09:28,834
This is a mechanical watch.

221
00:09:28,834 --> 00:09:30,901
It's got no battery in it.
You had to wind it up.

222
00:09:30,901 --> 00:09:32,334
It's all little cogs
and wheels.

223
00:09:32,334 --> 00:09:35,901
Does anyone in the audience have
a purely mechanical watch?

224
00:09:35,901 --> 00:09:38,200
- Nope, no one.
- Not on me.

225
00:09:38,200 --> 00:09:40,067
Not on you, okay.

226
00:09:40,067 --> 00:09:41,834
Good, nothing wrong
with an old watch.

227
00:09:41,834 --> 00:09:44,300
But it's expensive
for what it does,

228
00:09:44,300 --> 00:09:47,667
and you need to wind it.

229
00:09:47,667 --> 00:09:49,234
This is wrong.

230
00:09:49,234 --> 00:09:50,434
Now, this is a digital watch.

231
00:09:50,434 --> 00:09:52,033
This is a particular type
of digital watch

232
00:09:52,033 --> 00:09:53,634
that came out in the 70s.

233
00:09:53,634 --> 00:09:54,834
And to actually
get the display,

234
00:09:54,834 --> 00:09:57,767
you had to press the button
to see the time.

235
00:09:57,767 --> 00:09:59,801
Does anyone
have one of those?

236
00:09:59,801 --> 00:10:02,801
Okay, I'm glad, 'cause I'm
saying that's wrong and really--

237
00:10:02,801 --> 00:10:05,200
people could just
for stylistic reasons like it.

238
00:10:05,200 --> 00:10:07,300
But you had to press it
to find out the time,

239
00:10:07,300 --> 00:10:09,267
so you couldn't glance at your
watch surreptitiously

240
00:10:09,267 --> 00:10:10,567
in a meeting where
you're getting bored

241
00:10:10,567 --> 00:10:13,100
and find out
what time it was.

242
00:10:13,100 --> 00:10:15,501
And finally, now we've got
things like this,

243
00:10:15,501 --> 00:10:18,701
which is a mixed
digital-analog watch.

244
00:10:18,701 --> 00:10:19,868
So whatever takes your fancy,

245
00:10:19,868 --> 00:10:21,367
whether you like analog
or digital,

246
00:10:21,367 --> 00:10:22,400
you can glance at it.

247
00:10:22,400 --> 00:10:23,901
It's always on.

248
00:10:23,901 --> 00:10:25,501
It's battery powered.
You don't have to wind it up.

249
00:10:25,501 --> 00:10:27,567
And it's much cheaper
